  "faq_items": [
    {
      "q": "What color is Max Def Hunter Green, really?",
      "a": "A deep, earthy forest green with visible olive and dark brown granule accents. In direct Florida sun it reads as a clear forest tone; in shade it pulls toward dark gray-green. Far more committed to green than typical 'gray with a hint' SKUs."
    },
    {
      "q": "Will Max Def Hunter Green look natural on a typical Florida home?",
      "a": "Depends on the lot. On a wooded or hillside lot the color ties the house into the surroundings beautifully. On a flat suburban lot with mature palms or open lawn, it can read as an isolated choice. Best paired with mature landscaping rather than recently-cleared lots."
    },
    {
      "q": "Does Max Def Hunter Green fade over time?",
      "a": "Some. Green asphalt shingles use chromium-oxide pigments in the granule blend, which hold up well but drift slightly cooler over time. Expect a barely-visible shift toward gray-green over the first 10 years in Florida sun. Source: NRCA Asphalt Shingle Manual."
    },
    {
      "q": "Will Max Def Hunter Green make my house run hotter?",
      "a": "Slightly. Dark green asphalt absorbs similar solar heat to mid-dark gray or brown. Florida attic-temperature impact is 5 to 10 degrees Fahrenheit at peak summer versus a light gray. Proper ventilation and a radiant barrier reduce monthly cooling impact to under 20 dollars."
    },
    {
      "q": "Is this color rare?",
      "a": "Yes. Green asphalt SKUs are produced in smaller volumes than gray or brown and lead times can be longer. Plan a 2 to 4 week lead time and confirm stock with your installer before contract."
    },
    {
      "q": "How does Max Def Hunter Green pair with palm landscaping?",
      "a": "Well, especially with mature king palms or sabal palms. The deep green of the roof complements the cool blue-green of palm fronds rather than competing with it. Avoid pairing with vivid Bird-of-Paradise or hibiscus accents that can compete with the roof color."
    }
  ],
